    </p>
      <p class = "small-text">This may be the location of your Internet Service Provider.</p>
    <p>
      While most people nowadays have heard of cookies, many do not know how they work. When you access a
      website that
      uses cookies, that website assigns your co</p>mputer and its user a unique ID. The small text file containing this ID
      is called a "cookie," and is usually stored on your computer. The web server then collects information about your
      activities as you navigate its website, and will likely store your physical location and identifying information
      about your computer as well. The next time you visit that website, the cookie stored on your computer will help
      the web server recognize you and your previous activities. Cookies can be used to keep you logged in to a
      website, personalize the look of the page to your preferences, or track your activities.
    </p>
    <p>
      Another way a website can collect your data is through the use of scripts. When you visit a website, it is common
      to see the different elements on the page "pop" to life over the first few seconds. Large items, like complicated
      graphics, embedded video, and rolling ads, take longer to load onto the page than plain text. In that time, many
      websites are also executing invisible scripts that do things like deliver customized ads, gather information for
      web analytics services, or track where you have been.
